properties.neighborhood_overview: Frederiksberg is an old part of the Copenhagen area with beautiful old buildings and villas. We love living here because there are plenty of restaurants, cafés, shops and our favourite park - Frederiksberg Garden. Also, it is a 5-10 minute walk from the vibrant areas of Vesterbro and Nørrebro. Central Copenhagen is only a bike ride away too. We love this because it means you are close to everything but that you can also come back to a more quiet area at night.
properties.notes: If you are meeting friends in Copenhagen, it is possible to fit two extra people in our livingroom - one on the couch and one on our air matress. Please notify us in advance if you will be more than two people - also as you are not allowed to bring anyone else to the apartment during your stay without our knowledge.
properties.transit: Take the metro from the airport to Forum Metro Station, which is a seven minute walk from our apartment. Vesterbro Station is a 10-15 minute walk and Copenhagen Central Train Station is about a 20 minute walk away. There is a bike store two minutes from our place where you can rent bikes. The brand new public Copenhagen Bikes can also be rented on an hourly basis right by Forum Station. Bikes are the perfect way to see the city! If you arrive in car, there is parking in our street and the neighbour streets. It costs 35 kroner to park a full day. You can buy the parking ticket at SevenEleven.
properties.access: You'll have access to our entire apartment, when you stay with us. We have Apple TV and wifi, and a cozy back yard. There is a laundromat a five minute walk away if you need to do laundry while here. There will be tea, coffee, olive oil and spices for you to use, if you choose to cook at the house. All other food, you can easily buy at our favourite supermarket Rema1000 right by Forum Station, or the more luxury stores like Irma or Føtex - both a five minute walk away. There will be a light breakfast available consisting of traditional Danish dark bread, butter, jam, milk, oats and fruit. Please let us know if you do not wish to have the breakfast during your stay. If you are traveling with an infant, our apartment is also perfect as we just had a son in May 2016. There's a changing table and NaturesSway bed available to use for your baby while staying here, as well as some toys if you wish. Just let us know and we'll leave it out for you!
properties.interaction: We list our place when we are out of town, so unless our paths cross on the days of arrival and departure, you will have the apartment to yourself. This also means you have to be ok with possibly not meeting us at all. We have great experience with letting friends welcoming guests, if we are away upon your arrival.
properties.house_rules: We want you to feel welcome and at home, and in return we expect our guests to show respect and treat our furniture and belongings with care and attention. We kindly ask that you don't bring any other people to our apartment while living here. Also, please respect that this is a non-smoking home. We hope you will enjoy your cigarettes in our backyard instead. No pets are allowed in our building. If you should spill or break anything, please let us know as soon as possible in order to help fix it!

properties.host_about:
Hi' I'm Bettina. I love living in Copenhagen, especially in my own neighborhood. 
I live in a red brick house with my family at four, looking out at a nice little oasis of a garden. 

14 years ago my husband and I moved to this working class klondyke in an old area of Copenhagen because of the house and the location. The Metro came to town and suddenly we could get around the city smooth and easily. 
This was a place with options and soul. 

Today the area is a colorful pattern of creative people, families, schools, gyms, galleries and temples and churches of various religions. 
I love that this is a place with space for cats, dogs, ideas and the typical Danish broadmindedness. 

Cooking, eating and cooking are keywords in my family - especially classic Danish dishes. When our family does dine out, however, we often do it locally. The traditional Danish open-faced sandwich called Smørebrød is one of our favorites and there are plenty of smørrebrødsshops around. 
We also love The Korean place around the corner, not to mention enjoying a cup of Coffee and a piece of layer cake at cool Lagkagehuset in the shoppingstreet. 

We travel a lot with our two teenage boys Mikkel and Mathias. France is a favorite. But we are also typical Danes from the north. Both bright summer nights and long, dark evenings with fireplaces and candles in the fall and winter are greatly admired. 

In rain, fog and sunny weather I always ride my bike to work and Copenhagen never stops surprising me. My motto for the ride is to find a new route every day. Travelling around by bike, I can highly recommend.

We are looking forward to warmly welcome you.
